In addition, regardless of the types of model misspecification, keeping all other manipulated variables fixed, the population values for RMSEA can be noticeably different across estimation methods. For example, when fitting a one-factor model to a two-factor data with ρ = .90 (*p* = 30, λ = .80), the population values are .056 (ML), .033 (ULS), .045 (DWLS with asymmetric thresholds), and .046 (DWLS with asymmetric thresholds), respectively. It is noted that the direction of the effect of estimation methods on RMSEA was not consistent. That is, the ML-based RMSEA can be either smaller or greater than the population RMSEA obtained using least squares estimators (i.e., ULS or DWLS).

